{TEXT -1 229 "2.  Polynomials:  Intercepts and Sign.  There are severa
l features about the graphs of polynomials which are important to trac
k.  These features inform us about the behavior of the function.  Thos
e features include the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 57 "    a.    x-intercepts of the function   \+
                " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "                    \+
   Those values where the graph crosses the x-axis.  Those points are \+
solutions of the equation y = f(x) = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
105 "    b.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function where
 the values of the function are positive" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
215 "                       Those regions where the graph lies above t
he x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polynomia
ls, these regions are bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/-
 infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    c.    regions (interva
ls) in the domain of the function where the values of the function are
 negative" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Thos
e regions where the graph lies below the x-axis.  For a continuous fun
ction, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by
 the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 36 "    d.   y-intercept of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 107 "                       The value where the graph crosses
 the y-axis.  The value of the function when x = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 19 "    e.   end limits" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "  \+
                     For a polynomial, its values will become either a
rbitrarily large in a positive sense or arbitrarily large in a negativ
e sense as the domain values tend to infinity.  Graphically, the value
s on the graph will growth arbitrarily large positively (go up off the
 graph) or arbitrarily large negative (go down off the graph) as the d
omain values tend to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 87 "     \+
                  Similar behavior holds true for approaches to negati
ve infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 150 "For each of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the
 polynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally represent the feature
s of the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 90 ", for each polyn
omial find each of the above five graphcial characteristics (a.  thru \+
e.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.
   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = 6*x^2+24*x-8" "6#/%\"yG,(*&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG
\"\"#F(F(*&\"#CF(F*F(F(\"\")!\"\"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
