}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Polynomials:  Local extreme values
 and monotonicity.  Beyond information of the type gathered above abou
t intercepts and signs of a polynomial,  other important information c
an be determined from the so called \"critical points\" of a polynomia
l.  The critical points of a polynomial are the intercepts of its deri
vative.  Since the derivative of a function at a point represents the \+
slope of the tangent line to the graph of the that function at the poi
nt, then the intercepts of the derivative are places where the the tan
gent lines to the function are flat, i.e., are horizontal lines.  At s
uch places the graph is neither increasing nor decreasing.  Elsewhere \+
the graph must be either increasing or decreasing.  For a polynomial, \+
local extreme values (local maximums or local minimums) must occur at \+
the intercepts of the derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing features are important
 in analyzing the graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical points of the f
unction" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "                      For a po
lynomial these are the intercepts of the derivative of the polynomial
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g.    local maximum points of th
e graph of a function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "      \+
                These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function fo
r which the y-value is locally the largest value of the function.  Nea
rby values on the graph are lower.  For a polynomials the x-value of t
he point (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of the graph of a \+
function y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "                  \+
    These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which the \+
y-value is locally the smallest value of the function.  Nearby values \+
on the graph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (
x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 108 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the func
tion where the values of the function are increasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions where the graph r
ises as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For a continuous f
unction, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded \+
by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 257 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     j.    regions (intervals) in the domain of t
he function where the values of the function are decreasing" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions where the
 graph falls as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For a cont
inuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are \+
bounded by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 275 "For each
 of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.  Ch
oose a range that will optimally represent the features of the graph. \+
 Include the graph of the deriviative of the polynomial on the plot.  \+
 Plot the function in red and the derviative in green.   " }{TEXT 269 
4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 89 ", for each polynomial find each of the above te
n graphcial characteristics (a.  thru j.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
