nge, " }{TEXT 275 0 "" }{TEXT 276 2 "y=" }{TEXT -1 19 "range [, option
s]);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 6 "wh
ere " }{TEXT 277 4 "expr" }{TEXT 281 1 " " }{TEXT -1 24 "is a symbolic
 expression" }{TEXT 279 1 " " }{TEXT -1 48 "which represents the funct
ion to be plotted and " }{TEXT 278 1 "x" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 
282 0 "" }{TEXT 283 1 "y" }{TEXT 284 0 "" }{TEXT -1 44 " are the two i
ndependent variables used in  " }{TEXT 280 4 "expr" }{TEXT -1 25 "  to
 define the function." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }{TEXT 285 0 "" }{TEXT 286 6 "plot3d" }{TEXT 287 
0 "" }{TEXT -1 238 " command will generate a surface plot for the func
tion over the rectangular range specfied in the command statement.  Th
e surface plot can be rotated, tipped over and turned around to see th
e surface plot from all side and all viewpoints." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 278 "For each of the followin
g functions provide a plot which shows the graph.  Choose reasonable v
alues for the ranges of x and y.  Rotate, where appropriate, to presen
t a good view of the graph.  The last two graphs are implicitly define
d functions which require the Maple command " }{TEXT 297 0 "" }{TEXT 
298 15 "implicitplot3d " }{TEXT 299 0 "" }{TEXT -1 29 "which is part o
f the package " }{TEXT 300 0 "" }{TEXT 301 5 "plots" }{TEXT 302 0 "" }
